    "title": "The \u03b2\u2070 Frontier",
    "publication_date": "2026-04",
    "description": "<div>\n<div>MATH-11 established that &beta; = &pi;/4 is the unique conversion factor between L1 (taxicab) and L2 (Euclidean) metrics on circular geometry. Every factor of &pi; in a physics formula traces to this conversion &mdash; an angular integration over a circular or spherical subspace performed in rectilinear coordinates.</div>\n<br>\n<div>This gives a classification tool for QED coefficients. Each term in the Schwinger series a_e = &Sigma; A_n (&alpha;/&pi;)^n can be tagged by its &pi; content:</div>\n<br>\n<div>&beta;\u2070: no &pi;. The term comes from topology and number theory &mdash; Feynman diagram combinatorics (rational coefficients), nested radial integrations (&zeta; values), or specific momentum configurations (polylogarithms). No angular integration contributed.</div>\n<br>\n<div>&beta;&sup2;: contains &pi;&sup2;. One angular integration over one circular subspace of loop momentum. &pi;&sup2; = 16&beta;&sup2; &mdash; one L1/L2 conversion squared, or equivalently two L1/L2 conversions (one per angular coordinate on the 2-sphere).</div>\n<br>\n<div>&beta;\u2074: contains &pi;\u2074. Two independent angular integrations. Each contributes &pi;&sup2; = 16&beta;&sup2;.</div>\n<br>\n<div>The classification counts how many times the computation converted from rectangular to spherical coordinates. More &beta; powers means more spherical geometry in the diagram.</div>\n</div>",
